# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: blast-sequence-search
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] In bioinformatics, **BLAST** (**basic local alignment search tool**) is an algorithm and program for comparing primary biological sequence information, such as the amino-acid sequences of proteins , nucleotides of DNA and/or RNA sequences.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] A BLAST search enables a researcher to compare a subject protein or nucleotide sequence (called a query) with a library or database of sequences, and identify database sequences that resemble the query sequence above a certain threshold.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] For example, following the discovery of a previously unknown gene in the mouse, a scientist will typically perform a BLAST search of the human genome to see if humans carry a similar gene; BLAST will identify sequences in the human genome that resemble the mouse gene based on similarity of sequence.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] BLAST is a widely used bioinformatics programs for sequence searching.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] It addresses a fundamental problem in bioinformatics research.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] The heuristic algorithm it uses is faster for large-scale searches compared to methods like Smith-Waterman.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] This emphasis on speed is vital to making the algorithm practical on the huge genome databases currently available, although subsequent algorithms can be even faster.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] The BLAST program was designed by Eugene Myers, Stephen Altschul, Warren Gish, David J.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] Lipman and Webb Miller at the NIH and was published in J.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] BLAST builds upon FASTA, a previously developed program for protein and DNA sequence similarity searches.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] It incorporates a novel stochastic model developed by Samuel Karlin and Stephen Altschul.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] While BLAST is faster than any Smith-Waterman implementation for most cases, it cannot "guarantee the optimal alignments of the query and database sequences" as Smith-Waterman algorithm does.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] The Smith-Waterman algorithm was an extension of a previous optimal method, the Needleman–Wunsch algorithm, which was the first sequence alignment algorithm that was guaranteed to find the best possible alignment.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] However, the time and space requirements of these optimal algorithms far exceed the requirements of BLAST.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] BLAST is more time-efficient than FASTA by searching only for the more significant patterns in the sequences, yet with comparative sensitivity.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] This could be further realized by understanding the algorithm of BLAST introduced below.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] BLAST is also often used as part of other algorithms that require approximate sequence matching.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] BLAST is available on the web on the NCBI website.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] Different types of BLASTs are available according to the query sequences and the target databases.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] Alternative implementations include AB-BLAST (formerly known as WU-BLAST), FSA-BLAST (last updated in 2006), and ScalaBLAST.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] The original paper by Altschul, *et al.* was the most highly cited paper published in the 1990s.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] Input sequences (in FASTA or Genbank format), database to search and other optional parameters such as scoring matrix.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] BLAST output can be delivered in a variety of formats.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] These formats include HTML, plain text, and XML formatting.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] For NCBI's webpage, the default format for output is HTML.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] When performing a BLAST on NCBI, the results are given in a graphical format showing the hits found, a table showing sequence identifiers for the hits with scoring related data, as well as alignments for the sequence of interest and the hits received with corresponding BLAST scores for these.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] The easiest to read and most informative of these is probably the table.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] If one is attempting to search for a proprietary sequence or simply one that is unavailable in databases available to the general public through sources such as NCBI, there is a BLAST program available for download to any computer, at no cost.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] This can be found at BLAST+ executables.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] There are also commercial programs available for purchase.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] Databases can be found on the NCBI site, as well as on the Index of BLAST databases (FTP).
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] Using a heuristic method, BLAST finds similar sequences, by locating short matches between the two sequences.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] This process of finding similar sequences is called seeding.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] It is after this first match that BLAST begins to make local alignments.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] While attempting to find similarity in sequences, sets of common letters, known as words, are very important.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] For example, suppose that the sequence contains the following stretch of letters, GLKFA.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] If a BLAST was being conducted under normal conditions, the word size would be 3 letters.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] In this case, using the given stretch of letters, the searched words would be GLK, LKF, and KFA.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] The heuristic algorithm of BLAST locates all common three-letter words between the sequence of interest and the hit sequence or sequences from the database.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] This result will then be used to build an alignment.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] After making words for the sequence of interest, the rest of the words are also assembled.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] These words must satisfy a requirement of having a score of at least the threshold *T*, when compared by using a scoring matrix.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] One commonly used scoring matrix for BLAST searches is BLOSUM62, although the optimal scoring matrix depends on sequence similarity.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] Once both words and neighborhood words are assembled and compiled, they are compared to the sequences in the database in order to find matches.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] The threshold score *T* determines whether or not a particular word will be included in the alignment.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] Once seeding has been conducted, the alignment which is only 3 residues long, is extended in both directions by the algorithm used by BLAST.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] Each extension impacts the score of the alignment by either increasing or decreasing it.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] If this score is higher than a pre-determined *T*, the alignment will be included in the results given by BLAST.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] However, if this score is lower than this pre-determined *T*, the alignment will cease to extend, preventing the areas of poor alignment from being included in the BLAST results.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] To run the software, BLAST requires a query sequence to search for, and a sequence to search against (also called the target sequence) or a sequence database containing multiple such sequences.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] BLAST will find sub-sequences in the database which are similar to subsequences in the query.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] In typical usage, the query sequence is much smaller than the database, e.g., the query may be one thousand nucleotides while the database is several billion nucleotides.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] The main idea of BLAST is that there are often High-scoring Segment Pairs (HSP) contained in a statistically significant alignment.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] BLAST searches for high scoring sequence alignments between the query sequence and the existing sequences in the database using a heuristic approach that approximates the Smith-Waterman algorithm.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] However, the exhaustive Smith-Waterman approach is too slow for searching large genomic databases such as GenBank.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] Therefore, the BLAST algorithm uses a heuristic approach that is less accurate than the Smith-Waterman algorithm but over 50 times faster.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] The speed and relatively good accuracy of BLAST are among the technical innovations of the BLAST programs.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] Key steps of the algorithm include filtering low-complexity regions, identifying high-scoring word matches, and statistically evaluating alignments.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] *Make a*k*-letter word list of the query sequence.* Take *k*=3 for example, we list the words of length 3 in the query protein sequence (*k* is usually 11 for a DNA sequence) "sequentially", until the last letter of the query sequence is included.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] *List the possible matching words.* This step is one of the main differences between BLAST and FASTA.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] FASTA cares about all of the common words in the database and query sequences that are listed in step 2; however, BLAST only cares about the high-scoring words.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] The scores are created by comparing the word in the list in step 2 with all the 3-letter words.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] By using the scoring matrix (substitution matrix) to score the comparison of each residue pair, there are 20^3 possible match scores for a 3-letter word.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] For example, the score obtained by comparing PQG with PEG and PQA is respectively 15 and 12 with the BLOSUM62 weighting scheme.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] For DNA words, a match is scored as +5 and a mismatch as -4, or as +2 and -3.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] After that, a neighborhood word score threshold *T* is used to reduce the number of possible matching words.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] The words whose scores are greater than the threshold *T* will remain in the possible matching words list, while those with lower scores will be discarded.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] For example, PEG is kept, but PQA is abandoned when T is 13.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] *Organize the remaining high-scoring words into an efficient search tree.* This allows the program to rapidly compare the high-scoring words to the database sequences.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] *Scan the database sequences for exact matches with the remaining high-scoring words.* The BLAST program scans the database sequences for the remaining high-scoring word, such as PEG, of each position.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] If an exact match is found, this match is used to seed a possible un-gapped alignment between the query and database sequences.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] *List all of the HSPs in the database whose score is high enough to be considered.* We list the HSPs whose scores are greater than the empirically determined cutoff score *S*.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] By examining the distribution of the alignment scores modeled by comparing random sequences, a cutoff score *S* can be determined such that its value is large enough to guarantee the significance of the remaining HSPs.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] *Evaluate the significance of the HSP score.* BLAST next assesses the statistical significance of each HSP score by exploiting the Gumbel extreme value distribution (EVD).
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] (It is proved that the distribution of Smith-Waterman local alignment scores between two random sequences follows the Gumbel EVD.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] For local alignments containing gaps it is not proved.).
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] Note that $\lambda$ and $\mathrm {K}$ depend upon the substitution matrix, gap penalties, and sequence composition (the letter frequencies). $m'$ and $n'$ are the effective lengths of the query and database sequences, respectively.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] The original sequence length is shortened to the effective length to compensate for the edge effect (an alignment start near the end of one of the query or database sequence is likely not to have enough sequence to build an optimal alignment).
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] They can be calculated as $m'\approx m-{\frac {\ln Kmn}{H}}\;$ $n'\approx n-{\frac {\ln Kmn}{H}}\;$ where $\mathrm {H}$ is the average expected score per aligned pair of residues in an alignment of two random sequences.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] Altschul and Gish gave the typical values, $\lambda =0.318$ , $\mathrm {K} =0.13$ , and $\mathrm {H} =0.40$ , for un-gapped local alignment using BLOSUM62 as the substitution matrix.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] Using the typical values for assessing the significance is called the lookup table method; it is not accurate.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] The expect score *E* of a database match is the number of times that an unrelated database sequence would obtain a score *S* higher than *x* by chance.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] The calculation shown here is modified if individual HSPs are combined, such as when producing gapped alignments (described below), due to the variation of the statistical parameters.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] *Make two or more HSP regions into a longer alignment.* Sometimes, we find two or more HSP regions in one database sequence that can be made into a longer alignment.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] This provides additional evidence of the relation between the query and database sequence.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] There are two methods, the Poisson method and the sum-of-scores method, to compare the significance of the newly combined HSP regions.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] Suppose that there are two combined HSP regions with the pairs of scores (65, 40) and (52, 45), respectively.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] The Poisson method gives more significance to the set with the maximal lower score (45>40).
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] However, the sum-of-scores method prefers the first set, because 65+40 (105) is greater than 52+45(97).
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] The original BLAST uses the Poisson method; gapped BLAST and the WU-BLAST uses the sum-of scores method.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] BLASTn offers nucleotide to nucelotide searches.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] This is useful when trying to identify evolutionary relationships between organisms.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] tBLASTn used to carry out protein to translated DNA searches.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] This is useful when looking for similar protein-coding regions in DNA sequences that haven't been fully annotated, like ESTs (short, single-read cDNA sequences) and HTGs (draft genome sequences).
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] Since these sequences don't have known protein translations, we can only search for them using tBLASTn.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] BLASTx compares a nucleotide query sequence (can be translated into six different protein sequences) against a protein database.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] This tool is useful when the reading frame of the DNA sequence is uncertain or contains errors that might cause mistakes in protein-coding.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] BLASTx provides combined statistics for hits across all frames, making it helpful for the initial analysis of new DNA sequences.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] BLASTp, or Protein BLAST, is used to compare protein sequences.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] You can input one or more protein sequences that you want to compare against a single protein sequence or a database of protein sequences.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] This is useful when you're trying to identify a protein by finding similar sequences in existing protein databases.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] Parallel BLAST versions of split databases are implemented using MPI and Pthreads, and have been ported to various platforms including Windows, Linux, Solaris, Mac OS X, and AIX.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] Popular approaches to parallelize BLAST include query distribution, hash table segmentation, computation parallelization, and database segmentation (partition).
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] Databases are split into equal sized pieces and stored locally on each node.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] Each query is run on all nodes in parallel and the resultant BLAST output files from all nodes merged to yield the final output.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] Specific implementations include MPIblast, ScalaBLAST, DCBLAST and so on.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] MPIblast makes use of a database segmentation technique to parallelize the computation process.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] This allows for significant performance improvements when conducting BLAST searches across a set of nodes in a cluster.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] In some scenarios a superlinear speedup is achievable.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] This makes MPIblast suitable for the extensive genomic datasets that are typically used in bioinformatics.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] BLAST generally runs at a speed of O(n), where n is the size of the database.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] The time to complete the search increases linearly as the size of the database increases.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] MPIblast utilizes parallel processing to speed up the search.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] The ideal speed for any parallel computation is a complexity of O(n/p), with n being the size of the database and p being the number of processors.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] This would indicate that the job is evenly distributed among the p number of processors.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] This is visualized in the included graph.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] The superlinear speedup that can sometimes occur with MPIblast can have a complexity better than O(n/p).
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] This occurs because the cache memory can be used to decrease the run time.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] The predecessor to BLAST, FASTA, can also be used for protein and DNA similarity searching.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] FASTA provides a similar set of programs for comparing proteins to protein and DNA databases, DNA to DNA and protein databases, and includes additional programs for working with unordered short peptides and DNA sequences.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] In addition, the FASTA package provides SSEARCH, a vectorized implementation of the rigorous Smith-Waterman algorithm.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] FASTA is slower than BLAST, but provides a much wider range of scoring matrices, making it easier to tailor a search to a specific evolutionary distance.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] An extremely fast but considerably less sensitive alternative to BLAST is BLAT (*B*last *L*ike *A*lignment *T*ool).
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] While BLAST does a linear search, BLAT relies on k-mer indexing the database, and can thus often find seeds faster.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] Another software alternative similar to BLAT is PatternHunter.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] Advances in sequencing technology in the late 2000s has made searching for very similar nucleotide matches an important problem.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] New alignment programs tailored for this use typically use BWT-indexing of the target database (typically a genome).
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] Input sequences can then be mapped very quickly, and output is typically in the form of a BAM file.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] Example alignment programs are BWA, SOAP, and Bowtie.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] For protein identification, searching for known domains (for instance from Pfam) by matching with Hidden Markov Models is a popular alternative, such as HMMER.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] An alternative to BLAST for comparing two banks of sequences is PLAST.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] PLAST provides a high-performance general purpose bank to bank sequence similarity search tool relying on the PLAST and ORIS algorithms.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] Results of PLAST are very similar to BLAST, but PLAST is significantly faster and capable of comparing large sets of sequences with a small memory (i.e.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] For applications in metagenomics, where the task is to compare billions of short DNA reads against tens of millions of protein references, DIAMOND runs at up to 20,000 times as fast as BLASTX, while maintaining a high level of sensitivity.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] The open-source software MMseqs is an alternative to BLAST/PSI-BLAST, which improves on current search tools over the full range of speed-sensitivity trade-off, achieving sensitivities better than PSI-BLAST at more than 400 times its speed.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] Optical computing approaches have been suggested as promising alternatives to the current electrical implementations.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] OptCAM is an example of such approaches and is shown to be faster than BLAST.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] While both Smith-Waterman and BLAST are used to find homologous sequences by searching and comparing a query sequence with those in the databases, they do have their differences.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] Due to the fact that BLAST is based on a heuristic algorithm, the results received through BLAST will not include all the possible hits within the database.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] An alternative in order to find all the possible hits would be to use the Smith-Waterman algorithm.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] This method varies from the BLAST method in two areas, accuracy and speed.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] The Smith-Waterman option provides better accuracy, in that it finds matches that BLAST cannot, because it does not exclude any information.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] Therefore, it is necessary for remote homology.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] However, when compared to BLAST, it is more time consuming and requires large amounts of computing power and memory.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] However, advances have been made to speed up the Smith-Waterman search process dramatically.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] These advances include FPGA chips and SIMD technology.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] For more complete results from BLAST, the settings can be changed from their default settings.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] The optimal settings for a given sequence, however, may vary.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] The settings one can change are E-Value, gap costs, filters, word size, and substitution matrix.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] Note, the algorithm used for BLAST was developed from the algorithm used for Smith-Waterman.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] BLAST employs an alignment which finds "local alignments between sequences by finding short matches and from these initial matches (local) alignments are created".
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] To help users interpreting BLAST results, different software is available.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] Example visualizations of BLAST results are shown in Figure 4 and 5.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] These include identifying species, locating domains, establishing phylogeny, DNA mapping, and comparison.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] With the use of BLAST, you can possibly correctly identify a species or find homologous species.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] This can be useful, for example, when you are working with a DNA sequence from an unknown species.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] Using the results received through BLAST you can create a phylogenetic tree using the BLAST web-page.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] methods, so should only be relied upon for "first pass" phylogenetic analyses.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] When working with a known species, and looking to sequence a gene at an unknown location, BLAST can compare the chromosomal position of the sequence of interest, to relevant sequences in the database(s).
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] NCBI has a "Magic-BLAST" tool built around BLAST for this purpose.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] When working with genes, BLAST can locate common genes in two related species, and can be used to map annotations from one organism to another.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] BLAST can use genetic sequences to compare multiple taxa against known taxonomical data.
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] By doing this, it can provide a picture of the evolutionary relationships between various species (Fig.6).
[src:blast-sequence-search/blast-biotechnology] , since if the gene shows up in an organism outside of the ancestral lineage, then it wouldn't be classified as an orphan gene.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] In statistical hypothesis testing, **e-values** quantify the evidence in the data against a null hypothesis (e.g., "the coin is fair", or, in a medical context, "this new treatment has no effect").
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] They serve as a more robust alternative to p-values, addressing some shortcomings of the latter.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] In contrast to p-values, e-values can deal with optional continuation: e-values of subsequent experiments (e.g. clinical trials concerning the same treatment) may simply be multiplied to provide a new, "product" e-value that represents the evidence in the joint experiment.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] For this reason, e-values and their sequential extension, the *e-process*, are the fundamental building blocks for anytime-valid statistical methods (e.g. confidence sequences).
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] Another advantage over p-values is that any weighted average of e-values remains an e-value, even if the individual e-values are arbitrarily dependent.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] This is one of the reasons why e-values have also turned out to be useful tools in multiple testing.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] E-values can be interpreted in a number of different ways: first, an e-value can be interpreted as rescaling of a test that is presented on a more appropriate scale that facilitates merging them.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] Second, the reciprocal of an e-value is a p-value, but not just any p-value: a special p-value for which a rejection `at level p' retains a generalized Type-I error guarantee.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] Third, they are broad generalizations of likelihood ratios and are also related to, yet distinct from, Bayes factors.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] Fourth, they have an interpretation as bets.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] Fifth, in a sequential context, they can also be interpreted as increments of nonnegative supermartingales.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] Interest in e-values has exploded since 2019, when the term 'e-value' was coined and a number of breakthrough results were achieved by several research groups.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] The first overview article appeared in 2023.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] Let the null hypothesis $H_{0}$ be given as a set of distributions for data Y .
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] Usually $Y=(X_{1},\ldots ,X_{\tau })$ with each $X_{i}$ a single outcome and $\tau$ a fixed sample size or some stopping time.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] We shall refer to such Y , which represent the full sequence of outcomes of a statistical experiment, as a *sample* or *batch of outcomes.* But in some cases Y may also be an unordered bag of outcomes or a single outcome.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] The value taken by e-variable E is called the **e-value***.* In practice, the term *e-value* (a number) is often used when one is really referring to the underlying e-variable (a random variable, that is, a measurable function of the data).
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] A test for a null hypothesis $H_{0}$ is traditionally modeled as a function $\phi$ from the data to $\{{\text{not reject }}H_{0},{\text{ reject }}H_{0}\}$ .
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] Moreover, this is sometimes generalized to permit external randomization by letting the test $\phi _{\alpha }$ take value in $[0,1]$ .
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] Here, its value is interpreted as a probability with which one should subsequently reject the hypothesis.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] An issue with modelling a test in this manner, is that the traditional decision space $\{{\text{not reject }}H_{0},{\text{ reject }}H_{0}\}$ or $\{0,1\}$ does not encode the level $\alpha$ at which the test $\phi _{\alpha }$ rejects.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] This is odd at best, because a rejection at level 1% is a much stronger claim than a rejection at level 10%.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] A more suitable decision space seems to be $\{{\text{not reject }}H_{0},{\text{ reject }}H_{0}{\text{ at level }}\alpha \}$ .
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] The e-value can be interpreted as resolving this problem.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] where we denote a test on this **evidence** scale by $\varepsilon _{\alpha }$ to avoid confusion.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] That is: it is valid if it is an e-value.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] In fact, this reveals that e-values bounded to $[0,1/\alpha ]$ **are** rescaled randomized tests, that are continuously interpreted as evidence against the hypothesis.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] The standard e-value that takes value in $[0,\infty ]$ appears as a generalization of a level 0 test.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] This interpretation shows that e-values are indeed fundamental to testing: they are equivalent to tests, thinly veiled by a rescaling.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] for an alternative hypothesis $H_{1}=\{Q\}$ would yield traditional Neyman-Pearson style tests.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] Indeed, this maximizes the probability under Q that $\varepsilon _{\alpha }=1/\alpha$ .
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] This yields tests that are remarkably different from traditional Neyman-Pearson tests, and more suitable when merged through multiplication as they are positive with probability 1 under Q .
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] From this angle, the main innovation of the e-value compared to traditional testing is to maximize a different power target.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] This means $p^{\prime }=1/E$ is a valid p-value.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] Moreover, the *e-value based test with significance level $\alpha$ ,* which rejects $P_{0}$ if $p^{\prime }\leq \alpha$ , has a Type-I error bounded by $\alpha$ .
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] But, whereas with standard p-values the inequality (*) above is usually an equality (with continuous-valued data) or near-equality (with discrete data), this is not the case with e-variables.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] This makes e-value-based tests more conservative (less power) than those based on standard p-values.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] In exchange for this conservativeness, the p-value $p^{\prime }=1/E$ comes with a stronger guarantee.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] This means that a p-value satisfies this guarantee if and only if it is the reciprocal $1/E$ of an e-variable E .
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] Traditional p-values only satisfy this guarantee for data-independent or pre-specified levels.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] This stronger guarantee is also called the **post-hoc $\alpha$ Type-I error**, as it allows one to choose the significance level after observing the data: post-hoc.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] A p-value that satisfies this guarantee is also called a **post-hoc p-value**.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] As $p^{\prime }$ is a post-hoc p-value if and only if $p^{\prime }=1/E$ for some e-value E , it is possible to view this as an alternative definition of an e-value.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] Under this post-hoc Type-I error, the problem of choosing the significance level $\alpha$ vanishes: we can simply choose the smallest data-dependent level at which we reject the hypothesis by setting it equal to the post-hoc p-value: ${\widetilde {\alpha }}=p^{\prime }$ .
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] As a consequence, we can truly reject at level $p^{\prime }$ and still retain the post-hoc Type-I error guarantee.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] For a traditional p-value p , rejecting at level p comes with no such guarantee.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] Moreover, a post-hoc p-value inherits optional continuation and merging properties of e-values.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] But instead of an arithmetic weighted average, a weighted harmonic average of post-hoc p-values is still a post-hoc p-value.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] Conversely, any e-variable relative to a simple null $H_{0}=\{P_{0}\}$ can be written as a likelihood ratio with respect to *some* distribution Q .
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] Thus, when the null is simple, e-variables coincide with likelihood ratios.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] E-variables exist for general composite nulls as well though, and they may then be thought of as generalizations of likelihood ratios.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] The two main ways of constructing e-variables, UI and RIPr (see below) both lead to expressions that are variations of likelihood ratios as well.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] Two other standard generalizations of the likelihood ratio are (a) the generalized likelihood ratio as used in the standard, classical likelihood ratio test and (b) the Bayes factor.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] Importantly, neither (a) nor (b) are e-variables in general: generalized likelihood ratios in sense (a) are not e-variables unless the alternative is simple (see below under "universal inference").
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] Bayes factors *are* e-variables if the null is simple.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] If the null is composite, then some special e-variables can be written as Bayes factors with some very special priors, but most Bayes factors one encounters in practice are not e-variables and many e-variables one encounters in practice are not Bayes factors.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] Suppose you can buy a ticket for 1 monetary unit, with nonnegative pay-off $E=E(Y)$ .
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] The statements " E is an e-variable" and "if the null hypothesis is true, you do not expect to gain any money if you engage in this bet" are logically equivalent.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] This is because E being an e-variable means that the expected gain of buying the ticket is the pay-off minus the cost, i.e. $E-1$ , which has expectation $\leq 0$ .
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] Based on this interpretation, the product e-value for a sequence of tests can be interpreted as the amount of money you have gained by sequentially betting with pay-offs given by the individual e-variables and always re-investing all your gains.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] The betting interpretation becomes particularly visible if we rewrite an e-variable as $E:=1+\lambda U$ where U has expectation $\leq 0$ under all $P\in H_{0}$ and $\lambda \in {\mathbb {R} }$ is chosen so that $E\geq 0$ a.s.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] Any e-variable can be written in the $1+\lambda U$ form although with parametric nulls, writing it as a likelihood ratio is usually mathematically more convenient.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] The $1+\lambda U$ form on the other hand is often more convenient in nonparametric settings.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] As a prototypical example, consider the case that $Y=(X_{1},\ldots ,X_{n})$ with the $X_{i}$ taking values in the bounded interval $[0,1]$ .
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] According to $H_{0}$ , the $X_{i}$ are i.i.d. according to a distribution P with mean $\mu$ ; no other assumptions about P are made.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] Then we may first construct a family of e-variables for single outcomes, $E_{i,\lambda }:=1+\lambda (X_{i}-\mu )$ , for any $\lambda \in [-1/(1-\mu ),1/\mu ]$ (these are the $\lambda$ for which $E_{i,\lambda }$ is guaranteed to be nonnegative).
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] where ${\breve {\lambda }}|X^{i-1}$ is an estimate for ${\lambda }$ , based only on past data $X^{i-1}=(X_{1},\ldots ,X_{i-1})$ , and designed to make $E_{i,\lambda }$ as large as possible in the "e-power" or "GRO" sense (see below).
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] Waudby-Smith and Ramdas use this approach to construct "nonparametric" confidence intervals for the mean that tend to be significantly narrower than those based on more classical methods such as Chernoff, Hoeffding and Bernstein bounds.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] E-values are more suitable than p-value when one expects follow-up tests involving the same null hypothesis with different data or experimental set-ups.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] This includes, for example, combining individual results in a meta-analysis.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] The advantage of e-values in this setting is that they allow for *optional continuation.* Indeed, they have been employed in what may be the world's first fully 'online' meta-analysis with explicit Type-I error control.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] It follows that, for any significance level $0<\alpha <1$ , if the null is true, then the probability that a product of e-values will *ever* become larger than $1/\alpha$ is bounded by $\alpha$ .
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] Thus if we decide to combine the samples observed so far and reject the null if the product e-value is larger than $1/\alpha$ , then our Type-I error probability remains bounded by $\alpha$ .
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] We say that testing based on e-values *remains safe (Type-I valid) under optional continuation*.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] Mathematically, this is shown by first showing that the product e-variables form a nonnegative discrete-time martingale in the filtration generated by $Y_{(1)},Y_{(2)},\ldots$ (the individual e-variables are then increments of this martingale).
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] The results then follow as a consequence of Doob's optional stopping theorem and Ville's inequality.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] We already implicitly used product e-variables in the example above, where we defined e-variables on individual outcomes $X_{i}$ and designed a new e-value by taking products.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] Not all e-variables defined for batches of outcomes Y can be decomposed as a product of per-outcome e-values in this way though.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] If this is not possible, we cannot use them for optional stopping (within a sample Y ) but only for optional continuation (from one sample $Y_{(j)}$ to the next $Y_{(j+1)}$ and so on).
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] If we set $E:=1$ independently of the data we get a *trivial* e-value: it is an e-variable by definition, but it will never allow us to reject the null hypothesis.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] This example shows that some e-variables may be better than others, in a sense to be defined below.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] Intuitively, a good e-variable is one that tends to be large (much larger than 1) if the alternative is true.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] This is analogous to the situation with p-values: both e-values and p-values can be defined without referring to an alternative, but *if* an alternative is available, we would like them to be small (p-values) or large (e-values) with high probability.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] In standard hypothesis tests, the quality of a valid test is formalized by the notion of *statistical power* but this notion has to be suitably modified in the context of e-values.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] In the case of a simple alternative $H_{1}=\{Q\}$ , the e-power of a given e-variable S is simply defined as the expectation ${\mathbb {E} }_{Q}[\log E]$ ; in case of composite alternatives, there are various versions (e.g. worst-case absolute, worst-case relative) of e-power and GRO.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] Then the likelihood ratio e-variable $E=q(Y)/p_{0}(Y)$ has maximal e-power in the sense above, i.e. it is GRO.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] Let $H_{1}=\{Q\}$ be simple and $H_{0}=\{P_{\theta }:\theta \in \Theta _{0}\}$ be composite, such that all elements of $H_{0}\cup H_{1}$ have densities (denoted by lower-case letters) relative to the same underlying measure.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] where $p_{\curvearrowleft Q}$ is the **Reverse Information Projection (RIPr)** of Q unto the convex hull of $H_{0}$ .
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] is an e-variable (with the second equality holding if the MLE (maximum likelihood estimator) ${\hat {\theta }}\mid Y$ based on data Y is always well-defined).
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] This way of constructing e-variables has been called the **universal inference (UI)** method, "universal" referring to the fact that no regularity conditions are required.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] Now let $H_{0}=\{P\}$ be simple and $H_{1}=\{Q_{\theta }:\theta \in \Theta _{1}\}$ be composite, such that all elements of $H_{0}\cup H_{1}$ have densities relative to the same underlying measure.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] To explicate the plug-in method, suppose that $Y=(X_{1},\ldots ,X_{n})$ where $X_{1},X_{2},\ldots$ constitute a stochastic process and let ${\breve {\theta }}\mid X^{i}$ be an estimator of $\theta \in \Theta _{1}$ based on data $X^{i}=(X_{1},\ldots ,X_{i})$ for $i\geq 0$ .
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] In practice one usually takes a "smoothed" maximum likelihood estimator (such as, for example, the regression coefficients in ridge regression), initially set to some "default value" ${\breve {\theta }}\mid X^{0}:=\theta _{0}$ .
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] Effectively, both the method of mixtures and the plug-in method can be thought of *learning* a specific instantiation of the alternative that explains the data well.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] which resembles, but is still fundamentally different from, the generalized likelihood ratio as used in the classical likelihood ratio test.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] Its main disadvantage compared to RIPr is that it can be substantially sub-optimal in terms of the e-power/GRO criterion, which means that it leads to tests which also have less classical statistical power than RIPr-based methods.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] Thus, for settings in which the RIPr-method is computationally feasible and leads to e-processes, it is to be preferred.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] These include the z-test, t-test and corresponding linear regressions, k-sample tests with Bernoulli, Gaussian and Poisson distributions and the logrank test (an R package is available for a subset of these), as well as conditional independence testing under a *model-X assumption*.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] However, in many other statistical testing problems, it is currently (2023) unknown whether fast implementations of the reverse information projection exist, and they may very well not exist (e.g. generalized linear models without the model-X assumption).
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] In **nonparametric** settings (such as testing a mean as in the example above, or nonparametric 2-sample testing), it is often more natural to consider e-variables of the $1+\lambda U$ type.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] However, while these superficially look very different from likelihood ratios, they can often still be interpreted as such and sometimes can even be re-interpreted as implementing a version of the RIPr-construction.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] Finally, in practice, one sometimes resorts to mathematically or computationally convenient combinations of RIPr, UI and other methods.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] For example, RIPr is applied to get optimal e-variables for small blocks of outcomes and these are then multiplied to obtain e-variables for larger samples - these e-variables work well in practice but cannot be considered optimal anymore.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] There exist functions that convert p-values into e-values.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] Such functions are called *p-to-e calibrators*.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] Formally, a calibrator is a nonnegative decreasing function $f:[0,1]\rightarrow [0,\infty ]$ which, when applied to a p-variable (a random variable whose value is a p-value), yields an e-variable.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] A calibrator f is said to dominate another calibrator g if $f\geq g$ , and this domination is strict if the inequality is strict.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] An admissible calibrator is one that is not strictly dominated by any other calibrator.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] One can show that for a function to be a calibrator, it must have an integral of at most 1 over the uniform probability measure.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] One family of admissible calibrators is given by the set of functions $\{f_{\kappa }:0<\kappa <1\}$ with $f_{\kappa }(p):=\kappa p^{\kappa -1}$ .
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] Conversely, an e-to-p calibrator transforms e-values back into p-variables.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] While of theoretical importance, calibration is not much used in the practical design of e-variables since the resulting e-variables are often far from growth-optimal for any given $H_{1}$ .
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] Now consider data $X_{1},X_{2},\ldots$ arriving sequentially, constituting a discrete-time stochastic process.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] Let $E_{1},E_{2},\ldots$ be another discrete-time process where for each $n,E_{n}$ can be written as a (measurable) function of the first $(X_{1},\ldots ,X_{n})$ outcomes.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] In basic cases, the stopping time can be defined by any rule that determines, at each sample size n , based only on the data observed so far, whether to stop collecting data or not.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] For example, this could be "stop when you have seen four consecutive outcomes larger than 1", "stop at $n=100$ ", or the **level- $\alpha$ -aggressive rule**, "stop as soon as you can reject at level $\alpha$ -level, i.e. at the smallest n such that $E_{n}\geq 1/\alpha$ ", and so on.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] With e-processes, we obtain an e-variable with any such rule.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] Crucially, the data analyst may not know the rule used for stopping.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] For example, her boss may tell her to stop data collecting and she may not know exactly why - nevertheless, she gets a valid e-variable and Type-I error control.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] This is in sharp contrast to data analysis based on p-values (which becomes invalid if stopping rules are not determined in advance) or in classical Wald-style sequential analysis (which works with data of varying length but again, with stopping times that need to be determined in advance).
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] In more complex cases, the stopping time has to be defined relative to some slightly reduced filtration, but this is not a big restriction in practice.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] In particular, the level- $\alpha$ -aggressive rule is always allowed.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] Because of this validity under optional stopping, e-processes are the fundamental building block of confidence sequences, also known as anytime-valid confidence intervals.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] Technically, e-processes are generalizations of test supermartingales, which are nonnegative supermartingales with starting value 1: any test supermartingale constitutes an e-process but not vice versa.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] E-processes can be constructed in a number of ways.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] (again, in complex testing problems this definition needs to be modified a bit using reduced filtrations).
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] Another way to construct an e-process is to use the universal inference construction described above for sample sizes $1,2,\ldots$ The resulting sequence of e-values $E_{1},E_{2},\ldots$ will then always be an e-process.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] Historically, e-values implicitly appear as building blocks of nonnegative supermartingales in the pioneering work on anytime-valid confidence methods by well-known mathematician Herbert Robbins and some of his students.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] The first time e-values (or something very much like them) are treated as a quantity of independent interest is by another well-known mathematician, Leonid Levin, in 1976, within the theory of algorithmic randomness.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] With the exception of contributions by pioneer V.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] In these, the concept was finally given a proper name ("S-Value" and "E-Value"; in later versions of their paper, also adapted "E-Value"); describing their general properties, two generic ways to construct them, and their intimate relation to betting).
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] Since then, interest by researchers around the world has been surging.
[src:blast-sequence-search/e-value] In 2023 the first overview paper on "safe, anytime-valid methods", in which e-values play a central role, appeared.
[src:blast-sequence-search/fasta] The original FASTA program was designed for protein sequence similarity searching.
[src:blast-sequence-search/fasta] Because of the exponentially expanding genetic information and the limited speed and memory of computers in the 1980s heuristic methods were introduced aligning a query sequence to entire data-bases.
[src:blast-sequence-search/fasta] FASTA, published in 1987, added the ability to do DNA:DNA searches, translated protein:DNA searches, and also provided a more sophisticated shuffling program for evaluating statistical significance.
[src:blast-sequence-search/fasta] There are several programs in this package that allow the alignment of protein sequences and DNA sequences.
[src:blast-sequence-search/fasta] Nowadays, increased computer performance makes it possible to perform searches for local alignment detection in a database using the Smith–Waterman algorithm.
[src:blast-sequence-search/fasta] FASTA is pronounced "fast A", and stands for "FAST-All", because it works with any alphabet, an extension of the original "FAST-P" (protein) and "FAST-N" (nucleotide) alignment tools.
[src:blast-sequence-search/fasta] The current FASTA package contains programs for protein:protein, DNA:DNA, protein:translated DNA (with frameshifts), and ordered or unordered peptide searches.
[src:blast-sequence-search/fasta] Recent versions of the FASTA package include special translated search algorithms that correctly handle frameshift errors (which six-frame-translated searches do not handle very well) when comparing nucleotide to protein sequence data.
[src:blast-sequence-search/fasta] In addition to rapid heuristic search methods, the FASTA package provides SSEARCH, an implementation of the optimal Smith–Waterman algorithm.
[src:blast-sequence-search/fasta] A major focus of the package is the calculation of accurate similarity statistics, so that biologists can judge whether an alignment is likely to have occurred by chance, or whether it can be used to infer homology.
[src:blast-sequence-search/fasta] The FASTA package is available from the University of Virginia and the European Bioinformatics Institute.
[src:blast-sequence-search/fasta] The FASTA file format used as input for this software is now largely used by other sequence database search tools (such as BLAST) and sequence alignment programs (Clustal, T-Coffee, etc.).
[src:blast-sequence-search/fasta] FASTA takes a given nucleotide or amino acid sequence and searches a corresponding sequence database by using local sequence alignment to find matches of similar database sequences.
[src:blast-sequence-search/fasta] The FASTA program follows a largely heuristic method which contributes to the high speed of its execution.
[src:blast-sequence-search/fasta] It initially observes the pattern of word hits, word-to-word matches of a given length, and marks potential matches before performing a more time-consuming optimized search using a Smith–Waterman type of algorithm.
[src:blast-sequence-search/fasta] The size taken for a word, given by the parameter kmer, controls the sensitivity and speed of the program.
[src:blast-sequence-search/fasta] Increasing the k-mer value decreases number of background hits that are found.
[src:blast-sequence-search/fasta] From the word hits that are returned the program looks for segments that contain a cluster of nearby hits.
[src:blast-sequence-search/fasta] It then investigates these segments for a possible match.
[src:blast-sequence-search/fasta] There are some differences between fastn and fastp relating to the type of sequences used but both use four steps and calculate three scores to describe and format the sequence similarity results.
[src:blast-sequence-search/fasta] In this step all or a group of the identities between two sequences are found using a look up table.
[src:blast-sequence-search/fasta] The k-mer value determines how many consecutive identities are required for a match to be declared.
[src:blast-sequence-search/fasta] Thus the lesser the k-mer value: the more sensitive the search. k-mer=2 is frequently taken by users for protein sequences and kmer=4 or 6 for nucleotide sequences.
[src:blast-sequence-search/fasta] , represented as diagonals of a certain length in a dot plot, between the two sequences by counting k-mer matches and penalizing for intervening mismatches.
[src:blast-sequence-search/fasta] of highest density matches in a diagonal are isolated from background hits.
[src:blast-sequence-search/fasta] values are used for scoring k-mer matches.
[src:blast-sequence-search/fasta] This ensures that groups of identities with high similarity scores contribute more to the local diagonal score than to identities with low similarity scores.
[src:blast-sequence-search/fasta] The best 10 local regions selected from all the diagonals put together are then saved.
[src:blast-sequence-search/fasta] This time use the relevant scoring matrix while rescoring to allow runs of identities shorter than the k-mer value.
[src:blast-sequence-search/fasta] Also while rescoring conservative replacements that contribute to the similarity score are taken.
[src:blast-sequence-search/fasta] For each of the diagonal regions rescanned this way, a subregion with the maximum score is identified.
[src:blast-sequence-search/fasta] The initial scores found in step1 are used to rank the library sequences.
[src:blast-sequence-search/fasta] Here the program calculates an optimal alignment of initial regions as a combination of compatible regions with maximal score.
[src:blast-sequence-search/fasta] This optimal alignment of initial regions can be rapidly calculated using a dynamic programming algorithm.
[src:blast-sequence-search/fasta] The resulting score initn is used to rank the library sequences.
[src:blast-sequence-search/fasta] This joining process increases sensitivity but decreases selectivity.
[src:blast-sequence-search/fasta] above the average score expected from unrelated sequences in the library.
[src:blast-sequence-search/fasta] A 200-residue query sequence with k-mer 2 uses a value 28.
[src:blast-sequence-search/fasta] ) for each alignment of query sequence to a database(library) sequence.
[src:blast-sequence-search/fasta] region of step2 for calculating the optimal alignment.
[src:blast-sequence-search/fasta] , and calculates the statistical significance of the "opt" score.
[src:blast-sequence-search/fasta] For DNA sequences, a banded alignment is provided.
[src:blast-sequence-search/fasta] FASTA can remove complexity regions before aligning the sequences by encoding low complexity regions in lower case and using the -S option.
[src:blast-sequence-search/fasta] However, the BLAST program offers more options for correcting for biased composition statistics.
[src:blast-sequence-search/fasta] Therefore, the program PRSS is added in the FASTA distribution package.
[src:blast-sequence-search/fasta] PRSS shuffles the matching sequences in the database either on the one-letter level or it shuffles short segments which length the user can determine.
[src:blast-sequence-search/fasta] The shuffled sequences are now aligned again and if the score is still higher than expected this is caused by the low complexity regions being mixed up still mapping to the query.
[src:blast-sequence-search/fasta] By the amount of the score the shuffled sequences still attain PRSS now can predict the significance of the score of the original sequences.
[src:blast-sequence-search/fasta] The higher the score of the shuffled sequences the less significant the matches found between original database and query sequence.
[src:blast-sequence-search/fasta] The FASTA programs find regions of local or global similarity between Protein or DNA sequences, either by searching Protein or DNA databases, or by identifying local duplications within a sequence.
[src:blast-sequence-search/fasta] Other programs provide information on the statistical significance of an alignment.
[src:blast-sequence-search/fasta] Like BLAST, FASTA can be used to infer functional and evolutionary relationships between sequences as well as help identify members of gene families.
[src:blast-sequence-search/fasta] Statistical significance of the score is usually determined through a permutation test: the query data is randomly rearranged (the nucleotide/amino acid ratio unaltered), and the corresponding score computed.
[src:blast-sequence-search/fasta] When comparing scores, no assumptions are made on the basis of evolutionary models, instead opting for randomly sorting the underlying data as a cue for non-significance (null hypothesis).
[src:blast-sequence-search/fasta] This is opposed to BLAST, which employs a statistical test based on a modeled distribution (the Karlin-Altschul test statistic) derived from a substitution matrix (typically BLOSUM or PAM for amino acids).
[src:blast-sequence-search/fasta] Although this slows down hypothesis testing considerably, it also makes handling of unusual amino acid compositions possible.
[src:blast-sequence-search/sequence-database] In the field of bioinformatics, a **sequence database** is a type of biological database that is composed of a large collection of computerized ("digital") nucleic acid sequences, protein sequences, or other polymer sequences stored on a computer.
[src:blast-sequence-search/sequence-database] The UniProt database is an example of a protein sequence database.
[src:blast-sequence-search/sequence-database] As of 2013 it contained over 40 million sequences and is growing at an exponential rate.
[src:blast-sequence-search/sequence-database] Historically, sequences were published in paper form, but as the number of sequences grew, this storage method became unsustainable.
[src:blast-sequence-search/sequence-database] Searching in a sequence database involves looking for similarities between a genomic/protein sequence and a query string and, finding the sequence in the database that "best" matches the target sequence (based on criteria which vary depending on the search method).
[src:blast-sequence-search/sequence-database] The number of matches/hits is used to formulate a score that determines the similarity between the sequence query and the sequences in the sequence database.
[src:blast-sequence-search/sequence-database] The main goal is to have a good balance between the two criteria.
[src:blast-sequence-search/sequence-database] The need for sequence databases originated in 1950 when Frederick Sanger reported the primary structure of insulin.
[src:blast-sequence-search/sequence-database] He won his second Nobel Prize for creating methods for sequencing nucleic acids, and his comparative approach is what sparked other protein biochemists to begin collecting amino acid sequences.
[src:blast-sequence-search/sequence-database] Thus marking the beginning of molecular databases.
[src:blast-sequence-search/sequence-database] In 1965 Margaret Dayhoff and her team at the National Biomedical Research Foundation (NBRF) published *"The Atlas of Protein Sequence and Structure".* They put all know protein sequences in the *Atlas*, even unpublished material.
[src:blast-sequence-search/sequence-database] This can be seen as the first attempt to create a molecular database.
[src:blast-sequence-search/sequence-database] They made use of the newly computerized (1964) Medical Literature Analysis and Retrieval System (MEDLARS) at the National Institutes of Health (NIH).
[src:blast-sequence-search/sequence-database] The team used computers to store the data but had to manually type and proofread each sequence, which had a high cost in time and money.
[src:blast-sequence-search/sequence-database] In 1966 the team released the second edition of the *Atlas,* double the size of the first.
[src:blast-sequence-search/sequence-database] It contained about 1000 sequences, and this time was coined as an information explosion.
[src:blast-sequence-search/sequence-database] The NBRF was on the cutting edge of utilizing computers for medicine and biology at this time.
[src:blast-sequence-search/sequence-database] Dayhoff and her team made use of their facilities for determining amino acid sequences of protein molecules in mainframe computers.
[src:blast-sequence-search/sequence-database] The number of discovered sequences continued to grow allowing for a deeper comparative analysis of proteins than ever before.
[src:blast-sequence-search/sequence-database] This led to many developments such as, probabilistic models of amino acid substitutions, sequence aligning and phylogenetic trees of evolutionary relationships of proteins.
[src:blast-sequence-search/sequence-database] The entire sequencing process became fully automated.
[src:blast-sequence-search/sequence-database] The first nucleotide sequence database was created.
[src:blast-sequence-search/sequence-database] Previously known as the European Molecular Biology Laboratory (EMBL) Nucleotide Sequence Data Library (now known as European Nucleotide archive).
[src:blast-sequence-search/sequence-database] The project's goal was sequence and map all the genes in a human which required the capability to create and utilize a large sequence database.
[src:blast-sequence-search/sequence-database] We now have many sequence databases, tools for using them and easy access to them.
[src:blast-sequence-search/sequence-database] One of the largest being GenBank which contains over 2 billion sequences.
[src:blast-sequence-search/sequence-database] Records in sequence databases are deposited from a wide range of sources, from individual researchers to large genome sequencing centers.
[src:blast-sequence-search/sequence-database] As a result, the sequences themselves, and especially the biological annotations attached to these sequences, may vary in quality.
[src:blast-sequence-search/sequence-database] There is much redundancy, as multiple labs may submit numerous sequences that are identical, or nearly identical, to others in the databases.
[src:blast-sequence-search/sequence-database] Many sequence annotations are based not on laboratory experiments, but on the results of sequence similarity searches for previously annotated sequences.
[src:blast-sequence-search/sequence-database] Once a sequence has been annotated based on similarity to others, and itself deposited in the database, it can also become the basis for future annotations.
[src:blast-sequence-search/sequence-database] This can lead to a *transitive annotation problem* because there may be several such annotation transfers by sequence similarity between a particular database record and actual wet lab experimental information.
[src:blast-sequence-search/sequence-database] Therefore, care must be taken when interpreting the annotation data from sequence databases.
[src:blast-sequence-search/sequence-database] Most of the current database search algorithms rank alignment by a score, which is usually a particular scoring system.
[src:blast-sequence-search/sequence-database] The solution towards solving this issue is found by making a variety of scoring systems available to suit to the specific problem.
[src:blast-sequence-search/sequence-database] Searching algorithm often produce an ordered list lacking biological significance.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] The **Smith–Waterman algorithm** performs local sequence alignment; that is, for determining similar regions between two strings of nucleic acid sequences or protein sequences.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] Instead of looking at the entire sequence, the Smith–Waterman algorithm compares segments of all possible lengths and optimizes the similarity measure.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] The algorithm was first proposed by Temple F.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] Like the Needleman–Wunsch algorithm, of which it is a variation, Smith–Waterman is a dynamic programming algorithm.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] As such, it has the desirable property that it is guaranteed to find the optimal local alignment with respect to the scoring system being used (which includes the substitution matrix and the gap-scoring scheme).
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] The main difference to the Needleman–Wunsch algorithm is that negative scoring matrix cells are set to zero.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] Traceback procedure starts at the highest scoring matrix cell and proceeds until a cell with score zero is encountered, yielding the highest scoring local alignment.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] Because of its quadratic time complexity, it often cannot be practically applied to large-scale problems and is replaced in favor of computationally more efficient alternatives such as (Gotoh, 1982), (Altschul and Erickson, 1986), and (Myers and Miller, 1988).
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] Wunsch proposed a heuristic homology algorithm for sequence alignment, also referred to as the Needleman–Wunsch algorithm.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] It is a global alignment algorithm that requires $O(mn)$ calculation steps ( m and n are the lengths of the two sequences being aligned).
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] It uses the iterative calculation of a matrix for the purpose of showing global alignment.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] In the following decade, Sankoff, Reichert, Beyer and others formulated alternative heuristic algorithms for analyzing gene sequences.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] Sellers introduced a system for measuring sequence distances.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] In 1976, Waterman et al. added the concept of gaps into the original measurement system.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] In 1981, Smith and Waterman published their Smith–Waterman algorithm for calculating local alignment.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] The Smith–Waterman algorithm is fairly demanding of time: To align two sequences of lengths m and n , $O(m^{2}n+n^{2}m)$ time is required.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] Gotoh and Altschul optimized the algorithm to $O(mn)$ steps.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] The space complexity was optimized by Myers and Miller from $O(mn)$ to $O(n)$ (linear), where n is the length of the shorter sequence, for the case where only one of the many possible optimal alignments is desired.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] Chowdhury, Le, and Ramachandran later optimized the cache performance of the algorithm while keeping the space usage linear in the total length of the input sequences.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] In recent years, genome projects conducted on a variety of organisms generated massive amounts of sequence data for genes and proteins, which requires computational analysis.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] Sequence alignment shows the relations between genes or between proteins, leading to a better understanding of their homology and functionality.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] Sequence alignment can also reveal conserved domains and motifs.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] One motivation for local alignment is the difficulty of obtaining correct alignments in regions of low similarity between distantly related biological sequences, because mutations have added too much 'noise' over evolutionary time to allow for a meaningful comparison of those regions.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] Local alignment avoids such regions altogether and focuses on those with a positive score, i.e. those with an evolutionarily conserved signal of similarity.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] A prerequisite for local alignment is a negative expectation score.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] The expectation score is defined as the average score that the scoring system (substitution matrix and gap penalties) would yield for a random sequence.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] Another motivation for using local alignments is that there is a reliable statistical model (developed by Karlin and Altschul) for optimal local alignments.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] The alignment of unrelated sequences tends to produce optimal local alignment scores which follow an extreme value distribution.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] This property allows programs to produce an expectation value for the optimal local alignment of two sequences, which is a measure of how often two unrelated sequences would produce an optimal local alignment whose score is greater than or equal to the observed score.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] Very low expectation values indicate that the two sequences in question might be homologous, meaning they might share a common ancestor.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] Let $A=a_{1}a_{2}...a_{n}$ and $B=b_{1}b_{2}...b_{m}$ be the sequences to be aligned, where n and m are the lengths of A and B respectively.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] Construct a scoring matrix H and initialize its first row and first column.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] The size of the scoring matrix is $(n+1)*(m+1)$ .
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] Starting at the highest score in the scoring matrix H and ending at a matrix cell that has a score of 0, traceback based on the source of each score recursively to generate the best local alignment.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] Smith–Waterman algorithm aligns two sequences by matches/mismatches (also known as substitutions), insertions, and deletions.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] Both insertions and deletions are the operations that introduce gaps, which are represented by dashes.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] The dimensions of the scoring matrix are 1+length of each sequence respectively.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] All the elements of the first row and the first column are set to 0.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] The extra first row and first column make it possible to align one sequence to another at any position, and setting them to 0 makes the terminal gap free from penalty.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] Score each element from left to right, top to bottom in the matrix, considering the outcomes of substitutions (diagonal scores) or adding gaps (horizontal and vertical scores).
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] If none of the scores are positive, this element gets a 0.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] Otherwise the highest score is used and the source of that score is recorded.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] Starting at the element with the highest score, traceback based on the source of each score recursively, until 0 is encountered.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] The segments that have the highest similarity score based on the given scoring system is generated in this process.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] To obtain the second best local alignment, apply the traceback process starting at the second highest score outside the trace of the best alignment.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] The Smith–Waterman algorithm finds the segments in two sequences that have similarities while the Needleman–Wunsch algorithm aligns two complete sequences.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] Therefore, they serve different purposes.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] Both algorithms use the concepts of a substitution matrix, a gap penalty function, a scoring matrix, and a traceback process.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] One of the most important distinctions is that no negative score is assigned in the scoring system of the Smith–Waterman algorithm, which enables local alignment.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] When any element has a score lower than zero, it means that the sequences up to this position have no similarities; this element will then be set to zero to eliminate influence from previous alignment.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] In this way, calculation can continue to find alignment in any position afterwards.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] The initial scoring matrix of Smith–Waterman algorithm enables the alignment of any segment of one sequence to an arbitrary position in the other sequence.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] In Needleman–Wunsch algorithm, however, end gap penalty also needs to be considered in order to align the full sequences.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] Each base substitution or amino acid substitution is assigned a score.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] In general, matches are assigned positive scores, and mismatches are assigned relatively lower scores.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] Different base substitutions or amino acid substitutions can have different scores.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] The substitution matrix of amino acids is usually more complicated than that of the bases.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] Gap penalty designates scores for insertion or deletion.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] A simple gap penalty strategy is to use fixed score for each gap.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] In biology, however, the score needs to be counted differently for practical reasons.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] On one hand, partial similarity between two sequences is a common phenomenon; on the other hand, a single gene mutation event can result in insertion of a single long gap.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] Therefore, connected gaps forming a long gap usually is more favored than multiple scattered, short gaps.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] In order to take this difference into consideration, the concepts of gap opening and gap extension have been added to the scoring system.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] The gap opening score is usually higher than the gap extension score.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] For instance, the default parameters in EMBOSS Water are: gap opening = 10, gap extension = 0.5.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] Here we discuss two common strategies for gap penalty.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] where $W_{1}$ is the cost of a single gap.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] The gap penalty is directly proportional to the gap length.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] The simplified algorithm uses $O(mn)$ steps.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] When an element is being scored, only the gap penalties from the elements that are directly adjacent to this element need to be considered.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] where v is the gap opening penalty, and u is the gap extension penalty.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] For example, the penalty for a gap of length 2 is $2u+v$ .
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] An arbitrary gap penalty was used in the original Smith–Waterman algorithm paper.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] It uses $O(m^{2}n)$ steps, therefore is quite demanding of time.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] Gotoh optimized the steps for an affine gap penalty to $O(mn)$ , but the optimized algorithm only attempts to find one optimal alignment, and the optimal alignment is not guaranteed to be found.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] Altschul modified Gotoh's algorithm to find all optimal alignments while maintaining the computational complexity.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] Later, Myers and Miller pointed out that Gotoh and Altschul's algorithm can be further modified based on the method that was published by Hirschberg in 1975, and applied this method.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] Myers and Miller's algorithm can align two sequences using $O(n)$ space, with n being the length of the shorter sequence.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] Chowdhury, Le, and Ramachandran later showed how to run Gotoh's algorithm cache-efficiently in linear space using a different recursive divide-and-conquer strategy than the one used by Hirschberg.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] The resulting algorithm runs faster than Myers and Miller's algorithm in practice due to its superior cache performance.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] Take the alignment of sequences TACGGGCCCGCTAC and TAGCCCTATCGGTCA as an example.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] When linear gap penalty function is used, the result is (Alignments performed by EMBOSS Water.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] Substitution matrix is DNAfull (similarity score: +5 for matching characters otherwise -4).
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] This example shows that an affine gap penalty can help avoid scattered small gaps.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] The function of the scoring matrix is to conduct one-to-one comparisons between all components in two sequences and record the optimal alignment results.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] The scoring process reflects the concept of dynamic programming.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] The final optimal alignment is found by iteratively expanding the growing optimal alignment.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] In other words, the current optimal alignment is generated by deciding which path (match/mismatch or inserting gap) gives the highest score from the previous optimal alignment.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] The size of the matrix is the length of one sequence plus 1 by the length of the other sequence plus 1.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] The additional first row and first column serve the purpose of aligning one sequence to any positions in the other sequence.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] Both the first line and the first column are set to 0 so that end gap is not penalized.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] Take the alignment of DNA sequences TGTTACGG and GGTTGACTA as an example.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] Initialize and fill the scoring matrix, shown as below.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] This figure shows the scoring process of the first three elements.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] The yellow color indicates the bases that are being considered.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] The red color indicates the highest possible score for the cell being scored.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] The finished scoring matrix is shown below on the left.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] An element can receive score from more than one element, each will form a different path if this element is traced back.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] In case of multiple highest scores, traceback should be done starting with each highest score.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] The traceback process is shown below on the right.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] The best local alignment is generated in the reverse direction.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] An implementation of the Smith–Waterman Algorithm, SSEARCH, is available in the FASTA sequence analysis package from UVA FASTA Downloads.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] This implementation includes Altivec accelerated code for PowerPC G4 and G5 processors that speeds up comparisons 10–20-fold, using a modification of the Wozniak, 1997 approach, and an SSE2 vectorization developed by Farrar making optimal protein sequence database searches quite practical.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] A library, SSW, extends Farrar's implementation to return alignment information in addition to the optimal Smith–Waterman score.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] Cray demonstrated acceleration of the Smith–Waterman algorithm using a reconfigurable computing platform based on FPGA chips, with results showing up to 28x speed-up over standard microprocessor-based solutions.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] Another FPGA-based version of the Smith–Waterman algorithm shows FPGA (Virtex-4) speedups up to 100x over a 2.2 GHz Opteron processor.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] The TimeLogic DeCypher and CodeQuest systems also accelerate Smith–Waterman and Framesearch using PCIe FPGA cards.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] A 2011 Master's thesis includes an analysis of FPGA-based Smith–Waterman acceleration.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] In a 2016 publication OpenCL code compiled with Xilinx SDAccel accelerates genome sequencing, beats CPU/GPU performance/W by 12-21x, a very efficient implementation was presented.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] Using one PCIe FPGA card equipped with a Xilinx Virtex-7 2000T FPGA, the performance per Watt level was better than CPU/GPU by 12-21x.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] A similar method has already been implemented in the Biofacet software since 1997, with the same speed-up factor.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] Several GPU implementations of the algorithm in NVIDIA's CUDA C platform are also available.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] However, the same tests running on dual NVidia GeForce 8800 GTX cards are almost twice as fast as the Farrar implementation for all sequence sizes tested.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] A newer GPU CUDA implementation of SW is now available that is faster than previous versions and also removes limitations on query lengths.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] Eleven different SW implementations on CUDA have been reported, three of which report speedups of 30X.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] Finally, other GPU-accelerated implementations of the Smith-Waterman can be found in NVIDIA Parabricks, NVIDIA's software suite for genome analysis.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] In 2000, a fast implementation of the Smith–Waterman algorithm using the *single instruction, multiple data* (SIMD) technology available in Intel Pentium MMX processors and similar technology was described in a publication by Rognes and Seeberg.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] In contrast to the Wozniak (1997) approach, the new implementation was based on vectors parallel with the query sequence, not diagonal vectors.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] The company Sencel Bioinformatics has applied for a patent covering this approach.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] Sencel is developing the software further and provides executables for academic use free of charge.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] A SSE2 vectorization of the algorithm (Farrar, 2007) is now available providing an 8-16-fold speedup on Intel/AMD processors with SSE2 extensions.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] When running on Intel processor using the Core microarchitecture the SSE2 implementation achieves a 20-fold increase.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] Farrar's SSE2 implementation is available as the SSEARCH program in the FASTA sequence comparison package.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] The SSEARCH is included in the European Bioinformatics Institute's suite of similarity searching programs.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] Danish bioinformatics company CLC bio has achieved speed-ups of close to 200 over standard software implementations with SSE2 on an Intel 2.17 GHz Core 2 Duo CPU, according to a publicly available white paper.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] Accelerated version of the Smith–Waterman algorithm, on Intel and Advanced Micro Devices (AMD) based Linux servers, is supported by the GenCore 6 package, offered by Biocceleration.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] Performance benchmarks of this software package show up to 10 fold speed acceleration relative to standard software implementation on the same processor.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] Currently the only company in bioinformatics to offer both SSE and FPGA solutions accelerating Smith–Waterman, CLC bio has achieved speed-ups of more than 110 over standard software implementations with CLC Bioinformatics Cube.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] The fastest implementation of the algorithm on CPUs with SSSE3 can be found the SWIPE software (Rognes, 2011), which is available under the GNU Affero General Public License.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] In parallel, this software compares residues from sixteen different database sequences to one query residue.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] Using a 375 residue query sequence a speed of 106 billion cell updates per second (GCUPS) was achieved on a dual Intel Xeon X5650 six-core processor system, which is over six times more rapid than software based on Farrar's 'striped' approach.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] It is faster than BLAST when using the BLOSUM50 matrix.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] An implementation of Smith–Waterman named *diagonalsw*, in C and C++, uses SIMD instruction sets (SSE4.1 for the x86 platform and AltiVec for the PowerPC platform).
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] It is released under an open-source MIT License.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] In 2008, Farrar described a port of the Striped Smith–Waterman to the Cell Broadband Engine and reported speeds of 32 and 12 GCUPS on an IBM QS20 blade and a Sony PlayStation 3, respectively.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] Fast expansion of genetic data challenges speed of current DNA sequence alignment algorithms.
[src:blast-sequence-search/smith-waterman-algorithm] Essential needs for an efficient and accurate method for DNA variant discovery demand innovative approaches for parallel processing in real time.
[src:blast-sequence-search/substitution-matrix] In bioinformatics and evolutionary biology, a **substitution matrix** describes the frequency at which a character in a nucleotide sequence or a protein sequence changes to other character states over evolutionary time.
[src:blast-sequence-search/substitution-matrix] The information is often in the form of log odds of finding two specific character states aligned and depends on the assumed number of evolutionary changes or sequence dissimilarity between compared sequences.
[src:blast-sequence-search/substitution-matrix] It is an application of a stochastic matrix.
[src:blast-sequence-search/substitution-matrix] Substitution matrices are usually seen in the context of amino acid or DNA sequence alignments, where they are used to calculate similarity scores between the aligned sequences.
[src:blast-sequence-search/substitution-matrix] In the process of evolution, from one generation to the next the amino acid sequences of an organism's proteins are gradually altered through the action of DNA mutations.
[src:blast-sequence-search/substitution-matrix] over a longer period of evolutionary time.
[src:blast-sequence-search/substitution-matrix] Each amino acid is more or less likely to mutate into various other amino acids.
[src:blast-sequence-search/substitution-matrix] For instance, a hydrophilic residue such as arginine is more likely to be replaced by another hydrophilic residue such as glutamine, than it is to be mutated into a hydrophobic residue such as leucine.
[src:blast-sequence-search/substitution-matrix] (Here, a residue refers to an amino acid stripped of a hydrogen and/or a hydroxyl group and inserted in the polymeric chain of a protein.) This is primarily due to redundancy in the genetic code, which translates similar codons into similar amino acids.
[src:blast-sequence-search/substitution-matrix] Furthermore, mutating an amino acid to a residue with significantly different properties could affect the folding and/or activity of the protein.
[src:blast-sequence-search/substitution-matrix] This type of disruptive substitution is likely to be removed from populations by the action of purifying selection because the substitution has a higher likelihood of rendering a protein nonfunctional.
[src:blast-sequence-search/substitution-matrix] If we have two amino acid sequences in front of us, we should be able to say something about how likely they are to be derived from a common ancestor, or homologous.
[src:blast-sequence-search/substitution-matrix] If we can line up the two sequences using a sequence alignment algorithm such that the mutations required to transform a hypothetical ancestor sequence into both of the current sequences would be evolutionarily plausible, then we'd like to assign a high score to the comparison of the sequences.
[src:blast-sequence-search/substitution-matrix] To this end, we will construct a 20x20 matrix where the $(i,j)$ th entry is equal to the probability of the i th amino acid being transformed into the j th amino acid in a certain amount of evolutionary time.
[src:blast-sequence-search/substitution-matrix] There are many different ways to construct such a matrix, called a **substitution matrix**.
[src:blast-sequence-search/substitution-matrix] The simplest possible substitution matrix would be one in which each amino acid is considered maximally similar to itself, but not able to transform into any other amino acid.
[src:blast-sequence-search/substitution-matrix] This identity matrix will succeed in the alignment of very similar amino acid sequences but will be miserable at aligning two distantly related sequences.
[src:blast-sequence-search/substitution-matrix] We need to figure out all the probabilities in a more rigorous fashion.
[src:blast-sequence-search/substitution-matrix] It turns out that an empirical examination of previously aligned sequences works best.
[src:blast-sequence-search/substitution-matrix] We express the probabilities of transformation in what are called log-odds scores.
[src:blast-sequence-search/substitution-matrix] where $M_{i,j}$ is the probability that amino acid i transforms into amino acid j , and $p_{i}$ , $p_{j}$ are the frequencies of amino acids *i* and *j*.
[src:blast-sequence-search/substitution-matrix] The base of the logarithm is not important, and the same substitution matrix is often expressed in different bases.
[src:blast-sequence-search/substitution-matrix] One of the first amino acid substitution matrices, the PAM *(Point Accepted Mutation)* matrix was developed by Margaret Dayhoff in the 1970s.
[src:blast-sequence-search/substitution-matrix] This matrix is calculated by observing the differences in closely related proteins.
[src:blast-sequence-search/substitution-matrix] Because the use of very closely related homologs, the observed mutations are not expected to significantly change the common functions of the proteins.
[src:blast-sequence-search/substitution-matrix] Thus the observed substitutions (by point mutations) are considered to be accepted by natural selection.
[src:blast-sequence-search/substitution-matrix] One PAM unit is defined as 1% of the amino acid positions that have been changed.
[src:blast-sequence-search/substitution-matrix] To create a PAM1 substitution matrix, a group of very closely related sequences with mutation frequencies corresponding to one PAM unit is chosen.
[src:blast-sequence-search/substitution-matrix] Based on collected mutational data from this group of sequences, a substitution matrix can be derived.
[src:blast-sequence-search/substitution-matrix] This PAM1 matrix estimates what rate of substitution would be expected if 1% of the amino acids had changed.
[src:blast-sequence-search/substitution-matrix] The PAM1 matrix is used as the basis for calculating other matrices by assuming that repeated mutations would follow the same pattern as those in the PAM1 matrix, and multiple substitutions can occur at the same site.
[src:blast-sequence-search/substitution-matrix] With this assumption, the PAM2 matrix can estimated by squaring the probabilities.
[src:blast-sequence-search/substitution-matrix] Using this logic, Dayhoff derived matrices as high as PAM250.
[src:blast-sequence-search/substitution-matrix] Usually the PAM 30 and the PAM70 are used.
[src:blast-sequence-search/substitution-matrix] Dayhoff's methodology of comparing closely related species turned out not to work very well for aligning evolutionarily divergent sequences.
[src:blast-sequence-search/substitution-matrix] Sequence changes over long evolutionary time scales are not well approximated by compounding small changes that occur over short time scales.
[src:blast-sequence-search/substitution-matrix] The BLOSUM *(BLOck SUbstitution Matrix)* series of matrices rectifies this problem.
[src:blast-sequence-search/substitution-matrix] Henikoff & Henikoff constructed these matrices using multiple alignments of evolutionarily divergent proteins.
[src:blast-sequence-search/substitution-matrix] The probabilities used in the matrix calculation are computed by looking at "blocks" of conserved sequences found in multiple protein alignments.
[src:blast-sequence-search/substitution-matrix] These conserved sequences are assumed to be of functional importance within related proteins and will therefore have lower substitution rates than less conserved regions.
[src:blast-sequence-search/substitution-matrix] To reduce bias from closely related sequences on substitution rates, segments in a block with a sequence identity above a certain threshold were clustered, reducing the weight of each such cluster (Henikoff and Henikoff).
[src:blast-sequence-search/substitution-matrix] For the BLOSUM62 matrix, this threshold was set at 62%.
[src:blast-sequence-search/substitution-matrix] Pairs frequencies were then counted between clusters, hence pairs were only counted between segments less than 62% identical.
[src:blast-sequence-search/substitution-matrix] One would use a higher numbered BLOSUM matrix for aligning two closely related sequences and a lower number for more divergent sequences.
[src:blast-sequence-search/substitution-matrix] It turns out that the BLOSUM62 matrix does an excellent job detecting similarities in distant sequences, and this is the matrix used by default in most recent alignment applications such as BLAST.
[src:blast-sequence-search/substitution-matrix] It also turns out the BLOSUM computer code written by Henikoff and Henikoff does not exactly match the description in their paper.
[src:blast-sequence-search/substitution-matrix] Surprisingly, this commonly used "wrong" version has better search performance.
[src:blast-sequence-search/substitution-matrix] The PAM matrices are based on mutations observed throughout a global alignment, this includes both highly conserved and highly mutable regions.
[src:blast-sequence-search/substitution-matrix] The BLOSUM matrices are based only on highly conserved regions in series of alignments forbidden to contain gaps.
[src:blast-sequence-search/substitution-matrix] The method used to count the replacements is different: unlike the PAM matrix, the BLOSUM procedure uses groups of sequences within which not all mutations are counted the same.
[src:blast-sequence-search/substitution-matrix] Higher numbers in the PAM matrix naming scheme denote larger evolutionary distance, while larger numbers in the BLOSUM matrix naming scheme denote higher sequence similarity and therefore smaller evolutionary distance.
[src:blast-sequence-search/substitution-matrix] Example: PAM150 is used for more distant sequences than PAM100; BLOSUM62 is used for closer sequences than BLOSUM50.
[src:blast-sequence-search/substitution-matrix] A number of newer substitution matrices have been proposed to deal with inadequacies in earlier designs.
[src:blast-sequence-search/substitution-matrix] For a list of more models (including irreversible i.e. asymmetric and/or specialized ones), see the documentation for recent bioinformatic software including IQ-Tree, PhyML, and RAxML.
[src:blast-sequence-search/substitution-matrix] The real substitution rates in a protein depends not only on the identity of the amino acid, but also on the specific structural or sequence context it is in.
[src:blast-sequence-search/substitution-matrix] Many specialized matrices have been developed for these contexts, such as in transmembrane alpha helices, for combinations of secondary structure states and solvent accessibility states, or for local sequence-structure contexts.
[src:blast-sequence-search/substitution-matrix] These context-specific substitution matrices lead to generally improved alignment quality at some cost of speed but are not yet widely used.
[src:blast-sequence-search/substitution-matrix] Since the 2000s, an increasing amount of matrices are defined for subsets of proteins not optimally aligned by traditional "general-purpose" matrices.
[src:blast-sequence-search/substitution-matrix] Recently, sequence context-specific amino acid similarities have been derived that do not need substitution matrices but that rely on a library of sequence contexts instead.
[src:blast-sequence-search/substitution-matrix] Using this idea, a context-specific extension of the popular BLAST program has been demonstrated to achieve a twofold sensitivity improvement for remotely related sequences over BLAST at similar speeds (CS-BLAST).
[src:blast-sequence-search/substitution-matrix] With nucleotides only having four possible values (in most bioinformatic sequences), the emphasis lies not in setting fixed values in the matrix, but in designing parameterized models that fit the observed evolution of the input sequence as it's being aligned.
[src:blast-sequence-search/substitution-matrix] Although "transition matrix" is often used interchangeably with "substitution matrix" in fields other than bioinformatics, the former term is problematic in bioinformatics.
[src:blast-sequence-search/substitution-matrix] With regards to nucleotide substitutions, "transition" is also used to indicate those substitutions that are between the two-ring purines (A → G and G → A) or are between the one-ring pyrimidines (C → T and T → C).
[src:blast-sequence-search/substitution-matrix] Because these substitutions do not require a change in the number of rings, they occur more frequently than the other substitutions.
[src:blast-sequence-search/substitution-matrix] "Transversion" is the term used to indicate the slower-rate substitutions that change a purine to a pyrimidine or vice versa (A ↔ C, A ↔ T, G ↔ C, and G ↔ T).
